class MyStack {
public:
    MyStack() {

    }

    void push(int x) {
        q2.push(x);
        while (!q1.empty()) {
            q2.push(q1.front());
            q1.pop();
        }
        std::swap(q1, q2);
    }

    int pop() {
        int x = q1.front();
        q1.pop();
        return x;
    }

    int top() {
        return q1.front();
    }

    bool empty() {
        return q1.empty();
    }
private:
    std::queue<int> q1;
    std::queue<int> q2;
};
```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n)
space complexity: O(n)
energy implications: MEDIUM
explanation: This solution uses two queues to simulate a stack. The push operation takes O(n) time because it needs to move all elements from one queue to the other. The pop and top operations take O(1) time. The space complexity is O(n) because in the worst case, all elements are moved from one queue to the other.

